East Bay Carpool
details: Overview: The East Bay carpool regularly drives to BASK General Meetings. It meets in the parking lot of Wells Fargo Bank, 5801 Christie Ave, Emeryville. This is near the intersection of Powell and Christie. Meeting time is between 5:00pm and 5:30pm. With three sharing a car, the carpool is eligible to save time and toll costs by taking the carpool lane.

title: North Bay Carpool
details: Overview: The North Bay/Sonoma County carpool regularly drives to BASK General Meetings. It meets in the Park & Ride lot at the Lakeville Highway Exit in Petaluma (west side of Hwy 101). Carpools leave by 5:15pm. With three sharing a car, the carpool is eligible to save toll costs for the Golden Gate bridge.

title: Alviso
details:
Overview: New dock and ramp are already getting silted in at low tide. There are both low and high freeboard floats. It is 3.5 miles to the bay. You can also paddle up the Guadalupe Creek to explore. The park is open 8AM to sunset. There is a site host present 24/7.

Parking: Free parking for about 70 cars. Roughly 400' from the ramp. There is a loading area by the ramp.

Facilities: Restrooms and water about 200 yds from ramp. New and well maintained. There is a picnic area and Maria Elana's restaurant in town is a good place to stop and fortify yourself.

Address: 1160 Taylor St at the corner of Hope and Mill Streets.

Contact Info: Alviso Marina Park, 408-262-6980
County of Santa Clara, 408-358-3741

Links: Bay Area Water Trail - Alviso Marina County Park

title: Bar Bocce
details:
Overview: Destination at high tide (beach is sand). At low tide there is slippery mud and rocks. The easiest landing spot is the north side of the beach along the sea wall. The public access path to the beach is around the south side of the restaurant. The reason to come here is the restaurant.

Parking: Parking is free but very limited when restaurant is open. Best to arrive by kayak or park at the foot of Locust St at the far north end of the parking lot which allows 3 hours between 6AM and 2AM but no overnight.

Facilities: There is a bathroom in the restaurant for customers. Good pizza and a full bar. No other amenities.

Address: 1205 Bridgeway in Sausalito (foot of Pine St.) in the same parking lot as the Turney Street ramp.

title: Bayfront Park, Mill Valley (AKA Dog Park)
details:
Overview: High tide Launch. Then meander down to Richardson Bay. Bring binoculars. Good birding. Be sure to get back before low tide or else run a shuttle. Launch from the mud bank next to the footbridge or the new dock.

Parking: Parking is free but limited on the street. Weekends there is also parking at the adjacent school. it is about a 50yd carry to the beach and another 100yds to the new canoe dock. There is space to load and rig.

Facilities: Bathrooms are across the foot bridge by the public safety building or in sewage treatment plant (open Mon-Fri 7AM-4PM, Sat-Sun 7AM-2PM).

Address: Foot of Sycamore St.

title: Brickyard Park, Strawberry
details:
Overview: High tide Launch or Destination. The beach is approximately 100 yds from the street down a gently sloped concrete path. The beach is sand below a low rip rap wall and goes to firm mud which gets progressively softer as the tide goes out. At low tide the mud extends quite a ways into the bay. Plan to launch or land at mid to high tide. This is protected water but subject to brisk west wind in the summer.

Parking: Parking is on the street. There is space for about 12 cars with no time restrictions, including overnight.

Facilities: Porta potty, playground equipment, benches, picnic table and a trash can.

Address: 8 Great Circle Dr. Entrance to park is by the intersection of Seminary Dr and Great Circle Dr. Beach is about 100yds from street.

title: Harbor Cove Canoe Dock, Strawberry
details:
Overview: Free public dock is located between two McMansions at #40 Harbor Cove Way. Seals may haul out on nearby island. If they are there you can't launch. The dock is down a dirt path and the carry from the street is about 50'. Note that this area is closed from October 1- March 31 because of the migrating birds. Birds! Bring binoculars. It is a fairly low dock and in good repair.

Parking: Parking is on the road and very limited (2-8 spaces max). No time restrictions.

title: Fields Landing Boat Ramp
details:
Overview: Convenient to Eureka, the Fields Landing Boat Ramp is an excellent access to the southern portion of Humboldt Bay. By way of the Fields Landing Channel, which is dredged to approximately 30 feet depth, the harbor entrance can be reached by boats of any size.

details:
Overview: Van Damme beach is a great place to launch for exploring sea caves along the Mendocino coast or to go diving. The beach is somewhat sheltered from northwest swells and has easy access.

title: Little River, Albion
details:
Overview: Paddle upstream to explorer the river, or out to the ocean. Albion Cove Cove has a rocky bottom and full of rock crab. 35/day limit, 5inches or larger, fishing license required. Learn the difference between males and females, release the females because they spawn thousands of eggs each year and that's next year's crab.

Parking: $10 day use and launch fee combined

Facilities: Restrooms. Hamburger, Chilli, and crab chowder bar. Boat ramp.

title: Albion River
details:
Overview: Explore the Albion River or venture out into the Pacific. Mouth of the harbor is rock bottom with Rock Crabs a plenty! Fishing license required, 35 per day limit, 5 inches or larger. Just as sweet as Dungeness only less meat per crab and a little more work to get at it. "When it's good, it should cause you to sweat to get to it" Please learn the difference between males and females, release the females, they supply the population for the next year.

Parking: $10 launch fee

Facilities: Launch ramp, lunch counter, restrooms.

title: Navarro State Beach

title: Bay Point Regional Shoreline Park
details:
Overview: East Bay Regional Parks has recently installed a kayak/canoe launch dock. It is about 1000' from the parking lot so bring wheels. Do not even think of coming here at anything but high tide. At a 1' tide there is only about 3" of water. Right next door at McAvoy Harbor there is a nice launch ramp. When you come here think birds and bring binoculars. The slough is about 1/2 mile long and J shaped. If you paddle out to the Strait be prepared for wind and possibly strong currents both ebbing and flooding. It is 8 miles to Martinez and about the same to Big Break. From here go northeast to explore Chipps Island and Spoonbill Creek or east to Pittsburg Marina. It's about 10 miles west to Martinez for a longer trip. Currently there is a 90 degree turn to get from the ADA path to the gangway that requires lifting the boat to at least shoulder high. This will be changed!

Parking: Free. Hours are 8AM-5PM but they leave the exit gate open until 10PM. Curfew is 10PM-5AM. There are 12 spaces.

title: Point Pinole Regional Shoreline Park
details:
Overview: Kayak camping here! There is a great deal of mud here at less than high tide. The best lowish tide landing is right by the old pier. This spot has sand that goes to mud at low tide. The closest landing to the campsite is just north of it beside some eucalyptus trees (high tide only). The park is closed 10PM-5AM. If you are camping and come by car be there by 4PM. The wind howls here on summer afternoons. Expect a wild ride.

Parking: There is parking 1 1/2 mile from the campsite and beach. The park service has a shuttle van with a trailer that can haul kayaks too ($1 each way)! Check the shuttle schedule on the website. This service makes this a possible Launch as well as Destination. With a camping reservation, 4 cars can be parked at the campsite and 3 in the main lot are OK overnight. If you want to leave a car in the parking lot overnight (say, while you are on a multi-day trip) call and let the ranger know. Parking costs $3/car/day on weekends April-October.

It has plenty of parking and a boat rinse station (water faucet but no hose). There are numerous places that one can launch from the beach (oceanside). Basically the surf is non-existent on the west end of the beach and increases as you go east. The best put-in is at the Jetty Day Use Area which is at the furthest west point of the park. The carry from the car to the beach is about 30 feet and the site is protected from both wind and swell.

Parking: Day use fee $7 per vehicle (with 9 people or less). Park is open from 7AM to Sunset.

Facilities: Restrooms, picnic area, campground. The Miwok camp area is right across the road from the launch ramp and is for tent camping only. Bathrooms at the camping areas have showers. Camping is $35/night. That includes two cars and 9 people

title: Sonoma Creek at the Hwy 37 Bridge
details:
Overview: Public shore. Access is from the west bound highway only. It is 360 yards or 0.20 mile to the river so bring your kayak wheels. When heading to the river from the parking lot do not take the left hand, flat, paved path labeled Wildlife Viewing. No oh no. Instead take the right hand abandoned road and go to the end. Turn right along a dirt path to where the fisherpeople have made a trail down to the floodplain just north of the power tower. Here is a side creek that is a pretty easy launch. Or walk (you did bring your wheels didn't you) to the shore of Sonoma Creek. Why would anyone put up with so much hassle? 8 miles to Black Point, 14 miles to Vallejo, 7 miles to the Sears Point Boat Launch, 6.5 miles to Hudeman Slough. There's a lot to see to and from any of these places. This is a central location and the paddling is good. Note: duck hunting season is October to February.

Parking: Free parking for about 12 cars. Hide your valuables (lots of broken glass).

Facilities: None.

details:
Overview: The Napa River is a small creek here. The path from the drop-off zone to the river is about 100 yds along a level paved path and then a dirt path. Launch from a firm mud bank. Go down river to town of Napa or as far as you wish. There are a number of places to take out on the Napa River between here and Vallejo. Also, be aware that Trancas Park is in a high risk flood zone. Don't go here after heavy rains.

Parking: Free parking in the park for 6 cars. There is space on the adjacent street for about 10 Cars. Parking on the street overnight is OK. The park is closed sunset to sunrise.

Facilities: Bathrooms and a drinking fountain are located about 200 yds from the launch area on the river.

Address: 610 Trancas St in downtown Napa

Contact Info: City of Napa Parks and Rec. 707-257-9529

title: Horseshoe Cove, Presidio Yacht Club
details:
Overview: Horseshoe Cove is a protected cove just east of the north tower of the Golden Gate bridge. Depending on the tides, it is a great launch site for paddling to Angel Island or Out The Gate. Inside the cove it is protected and outside are some of the strongest currents and most violent tide rips in the Bay. It is only about 1/2 mile to Yellow Bluff. Launching is possible from the beach below the PYC. There is a new concrete ramp leading from the parking lot to the beach. The beach is home of the Tamalpais Outrigger Canoe Club. Their boats are stored on the beach. The beach is launchable at all tides. The Presidio Yacht Club is operated by Travis Air force Base and welcomes kayakers and the general public. Nice bar for apres-paddle snacks and drinks with wonderful views.

Parking: Free. 20-30 spaces. Overnight is possible with a permit obtained from the Headlands Visitor Center, 415-331-1540, 9:30-4:30PM daily.

Facilities: Restrooms and bar in the Presidio Yacht Club which is open Th-Fri,4-11PM, Sat 11-12 Midnight and Sunday 11-7PM. At other times there are porta-potties near the Coast Guard pier. There is a picnic table on the beach.

Contact Info: Marina Manager, Louis Canotas, 415-332-2319

title: Muir Beach
details:
Overview: Once upon a time Muir Beach was a great launching spot for coastal exploration and surfing practice. Now the beach is 1/4 mile from the parking lot. Some of this hike is on a flat boardwalk and the rest is on a dirt trail that goes up a hill and then down again. Bring wheels if you feel up for this. Otherwise come by kayak from Rodeo, Horseshoe Cove or Bolinas. The surf is generally gentle and spills. The very far NW beach is pretty free of tourists, is the most protected place to land and is "clothing optional".

Parking: Free for about 100 cars. The lot is open from 9AM-9PM

Facilities: 4 basic pit toilets in the parking lot (no running water). Also, there's a picnic table in the parking lot. The Pelican Inn is located right on the highway outside the parking lot for lunch. Hours: 11:30AM-3PM for lunch and 5:30-9PM for dinner. It is also a cozy little inn with rooms in the $250-$350 range!!

Address: Highway 1 over the hill from Mill Valley.

title: Mill Valley, Lone Tree Beach
details:
Overview: Destination from either Muir or Stinson beach. The beach is landable with sand at low tide to +4 ft tides where landing area is higher with rocks. Beach is suitable for a lunch stop and accessible by kayak only. There is a nice fresh water creek running into the ocean, Lone Tree Creek, as named on the charts.

Parking: None.

Facilities: None.

title: Bolinas
details:
Overview: Paddle out to Duxbury Reef or just play in the surf. Gentle sloping beach, spilling waves. Bolinas has lots of board surfers, and if you get anywhere near them, you should know about surf etiquette and right of way (see links below). There are two places to launch in Bolinas. Both are old concrete ramps to the beach. One is located at the end of Brighton Way. The other is at the end of Wharf Road at the entrance to the lagoon. At high tides the water comes right up to both ramps. Normally the channel into the lagoon has the lowest surf (if any) for surf chickens.

Parking: Free, on the street. Finding a place to park ANYWHERE in Bolinas is impossible on sunny weekends or holidays. There is space to unload at both ramps.

Facilities: Restrooms are by the tennis court, at the community center and also just east of the community center.

title: Dunphy Park
details:
Overview: Protected launch into Richardson Bay. Good put-in for trips to Angel Island or along the Sausalito waterfront. It gets quite muddy at low tide. The launch beach is firm mud and little rocks at high tide and soft slimy mud at low tide. Dunphy Parks underwent a massive facelift (2020). There is now more parking. Cass Gidley Marina (at the north end of the park) will have a kayak launch from its dock. The path to the old launching area is less than 100yds.

Parking: Parking free. There are 30-40 spaces. No overnight parking allowed.

Facilities: There are new bathrooms by the parking lot and bocce ball court. There is a drinking fountain.

Beach opens 30 minutes before sunrise and closes 30 minutes after sunset. Formerly home of Sea Trek. Currently home of Environmental Traveling Companions

Parking: Free, but limited. There are 7 green spaces for the public and it generally OK to park there all day. More parking off Liberty Ship Way South or at the Bay Model.

Facilities: Restrooms, drinking fountain, beach and restaurant.

title: Paradise Beach
details:
Overview: Marin County Park. Open during daylight hours. Fully developed park. Launch from concrete ramp next to pier. Launch is a long, steep downhill from parking. Bring wheels for the return. Better yet run a shuttle to somewhere flat. If there is a ranger present and it is not busy they will let you drive down to unload. Launch is rocky and dangerous at low tide. There is a beautiful white sand beach to the north of the ramp that belongs to the park. The stairs to it are formidable. It is a Destination not a launch. Be aware that the ferry and freighters kick up wakes that do not reach the beach or ramp (as surf) for several minutes after they disappear.

Parking: Fee schedule is: $5/car, M-F and $10/car on weekends in the summer. If you walk in or kayak in it is free. It is also free the first Saturday of each month. Pay at the iron ranger in the parking lot. The park is open: 7AM-8PM in summer; 7AM-7PM, Sept-Nov; 8AM-5PM in winter. It is also possible to make arrangements with the ranger to leave a car overnight if you are on a multiday trip.

Facilities: Bathrooms, drinking fountain, fishing pier, lawn, picnic area, BBQ grill, beach shower.

Address: 3450 Paradise Dr.

Contact Info: Park office, 415-435-9212
Mike Maraccini is the head ranger for Paradise Park.

title: Paradise Cay
details:
Overview: AKA Danny's secret launch. Nice dock to launch from. Good put-in for trips to Red Rock or Angel Island. Marina is private with public access to dock. None of the docks are gated. There is a newish ADA gangway next to the harbormaster's office.

Parking: Free parking at "Public Shoreline Access" spots. There are seven next to the Tiburon Yacht club and five spaces at the NW corner of the marina with four or five more on the street. The main parking lot has one entrance and has a sign that says "No Public Parking". The road in has an electric gate with a keypad for residents. Hmmm.

Facilities: Clean and well maintained public restrooms are part of the yacht club building and are open when it is open. There are also bathrooms in the harbormaster's building that are unlocked when it is open, i.e. M-F 9AM-5PM, Sat 9AM-3PM, closed on Sunday.

There is a gently sloping path from the street to the beach with two sets of stairs (one very funky and one wood). the park is open from 9AM-4PM but this is not posted. Watch out for happy running dogs!

Parking: Parking is very limited along the side of the road. 1 hour 8AM-6PM every day. There are only a couple unrestricted spots on the entire street.

details:
Overview: Nice launch beach for trips into the bay or Corte Madera Creek. Gravel and rocks, good at all tides. Easy access from East Bay and Marin. Watch out for ferries and wakes and pull your boat up high enough to escape the wash. The site was developed by the windsurfers. Windy! The wind blows down the creek and is brisk on summer afternoons.

Parking: Along the side of the road, close to launch, there are about 10 spaces. Free. Be sure to park well off the pavement. It's a busy street. The carry to the beach is down a small bluff on a dirt path.

Facilities: ADA-compliant porta-potty 100 yards from launch.

title: San Rafael, Loch Lomond Marina
details:
Overview: A nice launch spot for trips in the northern part of San Francisco Bay. The Marin Islands (off-limits), the Brothers, the Sisters, and Red Rock are all in reach. The whole area gets muddy at low tide. The marina is under a new owner and is undergoing massive redevelopment. A housing development has been added, Andy's Market relocated to beside the ramp and a kiddy playground incorporated. All these things mean less parking. More changes to come. The channel into the marina is dredged so there is always water there. As of May 2018 kayak launching at the ramp was free for kayakers. Ditto for the muddy beach at the far east end. The launch ramp is open 24/7.

Parking: The best place to park and to launch for free is on the far east side of the harbor. As you enter work your way left until you get to the far east end. There is very limited parking by the launch ramp.

Facilities: A bathroom has been built at the far east beach. There are porta potties beside the harbormaster's office (by the ramp). Andy's market is right there so no one will starve.

Address: 110 Loch Lomond Dr., San Rafael

Contact Info: Harbormaster, 415-454-7228 (hours for the harbormaster, 8AM-4:30PM Mon-Sat)

title: San Rafael, Bull Head Flat

Overview: Bull Head Flat is part of China Camp State Park. There is a gravel ramp, but it gets muddy at low tide. Wind surfers have cleared the area of rocks. Windsurfers! It does get windy (blowing from the west) especially on summer afternoons. Otherwise this is a great place to start an exploration of Gallinas Creek (Buck's Landing, McInnis Park, even the Marin Civic Center) or, going south, China Camp or McNear's Beach.

Parking: $5 day use fee. Parking is right beside launch. There are 14 spaces. The gate is open from 8AM-7PM (or sunset). No overnight parking.

Facilities: Restrooms are closed because of a fire. Never fear, there is a porta potty. China Camp State Park camping nearby at Back Ranch Meadows. This site has an outdoor shower, drinking fountain, picnic tables and BBQ grills.

title: San Rafael, China Camp State Park
details:
Overview: China Camp is a great place for easy paddles into San Pablo Bay, and to explore some of the small islands (Rat Island, The Sisters). It has a nice sandy beach, but gets muddy at low tide (less than 2'). May be crowded weekends. It is a State Park that is operated by Friends of China Camp and is open 8AM-sunset. This site is protected from wind and generally sunny when it is foggy everywhere else. Water is warm (well sort of) so it's a good place to practice paddling and rescue techniques--but not at low tide.

Parking: Day use fee, $5/car. Distance, car to water - close. There is parking beside the launch area and also up the hill nearer the gate as well as outside on the road.

Facilities: Restrooms, picnic tables, outdoor shower, grassy area. This is also an historical site so don't miss wandering around. Camping is at Backranch Meadows (3 miles west on N.San Pedro Rd).

Address: 899 North San Pedro Rd., San Rafael

title: McNears Beach, Marin County Park
details:
Overview: This Marin county park is a favorite among families on summer weekends. It has a sandy beach and provides easy paddling access to San Pablo Bay and The Sisters. It also has a pool with changing rooms and a bathroom with showers. Kayaks can be launched from the beach opposite the pool (very busy in summer and muddy at low tide) or at the far south end of the park where the overflow parking is located. Entry to the park is $10 in summer and $5 in winter and $2 if you arrive by boat. The hours are 7AM-8PM in the summer. The site is sheltered and sunny on days when it is blowing and foggy everywhere else.

Parking: Day use fee. the lot is large but often full on summer weekends. There is an overflow lot at the far south end that has the better kayak launch as well (gravel going to firm mud and then to soft mud). There used to be a launch ramp here and the remains create firm access at low tide.

Facilities: Fully developed park with parking and bathrooms, showers, pool etc. picnic tables, BBQ grills, snack bar (with beer) and fishing pier.

Address: 201 Cantera Way in San Rafael

Contact Info: Marin County Parks, 415-499-6387

title: Lawson's Landing
details:
Overview: Float south in the shallows and see Dungeness Crabs, jelly fish, bait fish, and seals. Cross over to the preserve and look at the elk. $8 entrance fee plus $3 per kayak launching fee. Inside Tomales Bay and protected from surf surge. This site provides access to the north end of Tomales Bay. There is a ramp. There is a day use fee and an overnight charge and camping.

Parking: yes

Facilities: Combination Deli and Bait Shop (don't get the two mixed up or lunch could be interesting), restrooms, one-hose wash off station.

title: Tomales Bay, Marconi Cove
details:
Overview: Marconi Cove is a sweet little put-in on the east shore of Tomales Bay, across the bay from Heart's Desire Beach. Ownership of the site is unclear but there has been a dirt launch ramp here for years which is pretty much usable at all tides. The surface is pebbles, sand and small rocks. From here you can go anyplace in Tomales Bay. Right next door to the south is Tomales State Park land which will eventually be developed. The wish list includes camping and a ramp. Be aware that wind comes from the north and can create significant chop.

Parking: Free in a dirt lot which gets pretty muddy when it rains. There are no other facilities.

Facilities: None. Tony's restaurant is just up the road.

ETC keeps a container of boats here and runs programs for special needs kids here.

Parking: The parking lot holds over 50 cars with lots more parking available up the hill. On summer weekends it's all full!! Day use fee of $8. 100 yds car to water. Gate is open 8AM-sunset.

title: Drakes Estero, (formerly Johnson's Oyster Farm)
details:
Overview: Drakes Estero (formerly Johnson's Oyster Farm) is located at the northern end of Schooner Bay and provides access to all areas of Drakes Estero. There are two places to launch. One is right next to the bathroom and is only about 10 yds from the parking lot. It gets REALLY muddy at low tide. The other is about 100 yds west over flat ground where the buildings used to be. It has a pebble beach that doesn't go to mud until fairly low tides. To avoid getting stuck in the mud, plan your trip around a high tide. Drakes Estero is closed each spring for seal pupping season, usually between March 1 and June 30.

Parking: Free parking for about 30-40 cars. No time restrictions but no overnight parking allowed.

Facilities: Well maintained one seater bathroom. That's it.

title: Drakes Bay, Limantour Beach
details:
Overview: Limantour Rd, which had been closed during summer 2020 due to fires is now open (Nov. 2020). Limantour Beach provides access to Drakes Bay, and is a good launch location for a coastal paddle. It usually has moderate surf that can be dumpy. The sand beach is wide and flat. There are two access points at this location. Note that Limantour Spit is closed March 1- June 30 for seal pupping. Also note: the meander under the bridge has been known to be used as a bail-out spot when the wind in Drakes Estero was too strong to paddle against. Did I mention the wind?

Parking: Free. Over 100 spaces. .3 mile to the beach at the west parking lot and .2 mile at the east parking lot (which only has spaces for 12 cars). Part of the path is hard dirt and the rest is soft sand. This is the same at both lots. Bring wheels and a couple of able-bodied friends. Parking closed 12AM-6AM.

Facilities: Six very basic pit toilets, an outdoor shower, and two picnic tables near the west parking lot. One pit toilet in the east parking lot. The signs say that fires and camping require permits. Ditto overnight parking.

Contact Info: Bear Valley Visitor Center, 415-464-5100

Links: Point Reyes National Seashore

title: Drakes Bay, Drakes Beach
details:

Parking: Free parking for over 50 cars. It is then about 100 yds to the beach. There is no formal loading area. The lot is closed 12AM-6AM unless you get a permit.

Facilities: October 2020: due to pandemic only the bathrooms are open. Normally there are well maintained restrooms with changing areas, bookstore, National Park Service visitor's center, outdoor shower that doesn't work, picnic tables and BBQs. Evidently fires are OK on the beach with a permit.

Address: Take Sir Francis Drake Blvd out past North Beach and look for the sign. Take a left on Drake's Beach Rd.

title: Estero Americano
details:
Overview: Flat water paddling through cow pastures to a sandy beach at the mouth of the Estero. The important thing to know is whether or not the mouth of the Estero is open. If open then the Estero is subject to the tide and is very muddy at low tide. Also know that ALL the land bordering the Estero is private and they don't want trespassers. However, as you near the mouth the land to the north belongs to the Sonoma Land Trust. The beach on the south of the Estero, above the high tide line, is private. It is 7 miles to the beach.

Parking: Free, but limited. Please be sensitive to the residents and don't obstruct emergency access when parking. The access is just east and below the bridge over the Estero on Valley Ford Rd.

Facilities: None.

title: San Francisco, Crissy Field
details:
Overview: Crissy Field is a great launch site for paddles along the San Francisco waterfront. Be aware that the currents can be strong here, it can be very windy, there can be wind opposing current (big chop) and that there will be a fair amount of boat traffic. Crissy Field is a pretty busy place and a favorite of windsurfers and kite boarders as well as tourist, joggers, dog walkers etc. etc. The beach itself is sand and usable at all tides. It often has some little surf. Often it has no surf.

Parking: Ample free parking. There is a free electric charging station at the far east end of the parking lot. There are no time restrictions. Overnight parking might be allowed. At least it is not disallowed. There is no formal loading zone. The distance to the beach varies depending on where you park.

Facilities: Clean restrooms and changing rooms. Drinking fountain and an outdoor shower. Also a dog rinsing spot! There are picnic tables and a BBQ by the bathrooms. The Warming Hut at the west end of the beach has food and a touristy shop. There is no place to launch there and has pay parking 10AM-5PM on weekends.

Contact Info: GGNRA (Crissy Field Center) 415-561-7690

Parking: Parking is free but very limited due to heavy use by other people. Park as close to the harbormaster's office as possible. Parking is permitted 6AM-10PM in non-permitted spaces. No overnight parking allowed. There is ia rigging area in the parking lot, near the gate, beside the dumpster.

title: San Francisco, Aquatic Park
details:
Overview: This San Francisco waterfront park houses several historic ships. It has a sandy beach, and is very protected. It makes for a good launch or rest stop for paddles along the San Francisco waterfront. When launching or landing, be aware of swimmers in the water. Buoys mark the swimming area. South End and Dolphin clubs are located here. Due to the awful parking think destination rather than launch. The beach is usable at all tide levels. Once out of this lagoon there are strong currents, strong wind and boat traffic. Paddle under the piers to avoid all three.

Parking: Limited street parking at the bottom of Van Ness, Hyde or Polk. At the bottom of Polk there are wide paved ramps that lead around both end of the Maritime Museum. The carry is about 100 yds. Van Ness and Hyde Streets are closer. Although parking is free you have a better chance of winning the lottery. If by accident you find a spot it will have a 4 hour time limit between 5AM and 5PM. There is no place to unload or rig your boat. Good luck.

Facilities: You can find restrooms in the Maritime Museum (hours are 10AM-4PM daily) and on the Hyde Street Pier. There are many restaurants and a chi-chi hotel right across the street.

Address: Foot of Van Ness, Hyde and Polk Streets

details:

It is ADA accessible, it has racks to put your boat on when you get out, it is behind a locked gate so you can leave for lunch or overnight or wherever without worrying about your boat. Security will let you in when you come back. It is free. It located on the east side of Pier 39 next to the street. Because parking and traffic are outrageous this is definitely a Destination. Come here from the east Bay, from Horseshoe Cove, from Pier 52... Wear something cool under your drysuit. Oh, this is a busy commercial harbor so keep your eyes peeled.

Parking: Paid garages are nearby if you think you need to come by car. Be prepared to mortgage the house to get your car back.

Facilities: Restrooms, restaurants, tourists. Harbormaster's office hours are 9AM-5PM daily.

details:

The site is home to Kayaks Unlimited, a non-motorized boating co-op. They have a secure storage container and boat storage of members boats is possible. The site is owned by the Port of San Francisco and there are plans to put in a public toilet...sometime. There is a dock but it is locked and unusable. details:

The park is fairly protected but is in the same wind tunnel that makes Candlestick a favorite of windsurfers. From here paddle south to Candlestick or north to destinations in SF or even cross the Bay to Alameda Island or San Leandro. For a short paddle go north to Heron Head park for a picnic. There is a possible alternate launch directly behind the lower parking lot. High tide only.

title: Candlestick Point State Recreation Area, San Francisco
details:
Overview: There are two launch spots in the park about 50 yds apart. One is at the far south end at Windsurfers Circle and the other, about midway between the park entrance and Windsurfers Circle, is a beautiful, east facing, white sand beach that goes to very serious mud at low tide. Bear in mind that places with names like Windsurfers Circle can have howling wind. Also note that the windsurfers have cleared a path through the rocks to the water making this usable at mid as well as high tides.

Parking: Parking is plentiful and free. The park is open Sat-Wed, 8AM-5PM. Rangers warn about car break-ins in the parking lot.

Facilities: Facilities include restrooms, picnic tables, BBQ grills and running water. There is a camping area out by the fishing pier. It has 6 sites, each with a flat spot for a tent, picnic table and BBQ grill. New bathrooms are near the pier. Future plans include a launch ramp near the camping area. Facilities: There are clean, well maintained, bathrooms with an outdoor shower and drinking fountain by the parking lot. There are picnic tables and a BBQ. There are astroturf rigging areas at both ends of the parking lot. A couple kiteboarding outfitters have storage containers here.

title: Richmond, Ferry Point
details:
Overview: A good launch spot for trips in the central San Francisco Bay. There is a sand beach which fronts to the deep-water, dredged channel going to the Richmond Harbor. The beach is usable at all tides. There is a new paved, ADA-accessible path that leads from the parking lot to the tideline. The beach faces south and tends to collect flotsam and jetsam. From here you can poke around the Richmond Harbor (historically interesting), go to Red Rock, Pt. San Pablo Yacht Harbor, Berkeley or Angel Island. Check the tides and go with the flow.

Parking: Free parking in a large lot that is open from 8AM-4PM. there are 31 spaces plus 18 in a nearby lot. It is about 70 yds to the launch from the lot. Street parking is also available, and needed, as this is a very popular spot on weekends. They leave the exit gate open so you can get out after hours. There have been reports of vehicle break-ins. Do not leave anything of value out in the open in your car. It is likely that the development of "Terminal One" next to Ferry Point will make the parking situation worse. No overnight parking.

Facilities: New restrooms and a drinking fountain in the parking lot. Three stars out of 4. There is also three level outdoor shower. There is a picnic area with BBQs.

Address: At the corner of Dornan Dr and Brickyard Cove Rd.

The windsurfers have created a path through the rip rap beside the former site of Hs Lordships restaurant (closed in 2018). There is a nice beach opposite the Strawbale Hut.

Facilities: There are two clean, well maintained bathrooms. There is a shower behind the bathrooms and drinking fountains as well as a hose for washing off gear. There are also several picnic tables. There are fenced off areas for Stacked Adventures (rents kayaks), Okalani Outrigger Canoe club and a small boat sailing organization. There is a rigging area beside the bathrooms and the distance to the beach is 20-30 yards.

title: Fitzgerald Marine Reserve
details:
Overview: This site can be a launch or destination or an out-and-back. You can come here from either Linda Mar or Montara Beach. Finding the path for safe landing is tricky if you have not been here before. It is somewhat protected put-in, best used in smaller conditions. An outer reef provides some protection, but at low tide, the rocks are a popular haul-out spot for seals, so this site is best used at higher tides. The best path out onto the ocean is to head diagonally to the northwest. On bigger days the ocean outside this spot has numerous boomers. Exercise caution. Depending on the height of the tide you may be launching from a sand beach, from gravel or from rocks. The conditions are very affected by the tide. Lower tide means choppy conditions. Unless you have the skills you might not want to paddle over the reef. If you do have the skills rock gardening is fun! Heading south, round Pillar Point and land in the harbor. You did run a shuttle didn't you?

This location is a marine reserve. Do not flush the seals. Only smaller groups of kayakers (less than 8) are tolerated by the rangers.

Parking: Free. However you do need wheels to get to the end of the point from the parking lot and then you need to take your boat down (and up) stairs, over a creek and around rocks. Wear sturdy shoes that can get wet. Rig in the parking lot. There are about 50 spaces in the parking lot. It is 30-50 yds from the parking lot to the beach. Hours are 8AM-sunset. No overnight parking.

Facilities: Restrooms and a drinking fountain nearby. No camping.

title: Monterey Bay State Beach
details:
Overview: This is a great location, where you can select the size of surf you want, and where you are unlikely to encounter territorial board surfers. Starting at Monterey Bay Kayaks near the wharf, follow the shoreline eastward and curve northeastward toward Seaside and Sand City until you find the size surf you want. Due to shielding by the Monterey Peninsula, surf is negligible near the wharf and gets progressively larger as you go along the shore. The number of board surfers is small, and they are friendly if you show good surf etiquette. There tends to be a good soup zone of frothy white stuff between the break and shore, where you can hang out and get used to the feel of on-rushing water. Then, go out to the break and practice. A good access point is from Casa Verde Way, a mile east of the wharf from Del Monte Avenue.

Turn onto Casa Verde Way from Del Monte Avenue or Highway 1, going north toward the beach. Immediately past Del Monte Avenue, the road splits into one-way streets; go right (on Surf Way) and proceed to the beach (Tide Avenue).

details:
Overview: Located 1/2 mile out the gate this is a nice spot to land with relatively small surf. Interesting geology: outcrops of folded red ribbon chert. The beach faces south, is steep, and the surf dumps. The easiest landing is at the far west end.

Parking: Unless you have a camping reservation there is no parking. The entrance on Conzelman Rd is gated and locked. Even with parking the distance from the campground to the beach is difficult--about 100yds over a berm and down a set of stairs to the beach. And poison oak...

Facilities: Restrooms, picnic tables, camping with reservations. Spectacular views at night!

Contact Info: http://www.recreation.gov Click camping and enter Kirby Cove. Or call the Headlands Visitor Center for more info at 415-331-1540.

Links: http://www.recreation.gov

title: Point Bonita Arch
details:
Overview: Paddling through the arch beneath the Pt. Bonita lighthouse is one of the greatest paddling experiences in the Bay area. Alas, it needs to be really calm to do this. Interesting geology: great outcrops of pillow basalt in the cliffs and the arch.

WARNING: most of the shoreline of nearby Bonita Cove is now closed to boating within 300 ft. of shore. See links below.

Links: Closure maps

title: Rodeo Cove
Rodeo Cove (South End)
details:
Overview: Sandy beach with relatively small surf. Good lunch spot.

title: Red Rock Island
details:
Overview: Red Rock is accessible and landable on all sides. There are strong currents flowing past so be mindful of the tide and plan accordingly. It is located right beside the shipping lanes so there are ferries and freighters to watch out for. Red Rock is owned by an ex-pat and has been for sale for years. The island above the high tide line is private property, so don't trespass. Depending on the tidal currents it is an easy paddle from the Richmond shoreline. Do not get close to the Chevron Pier or you will get yelled at or maybe arrested. More planning is required to come from Marin.

Facilities: None

Address: Red Rock sits just south of the Richmond Bridge. It is about 3 miles from either San Quentin in Marin or Ferry Point in Point Richmond.

title: Riviera de Garbage
details:
Overview: Rocky beach at former dump site.

Facilities: Picnic table above beach. No restroom.

title: Angel Island, West Garrison
details:
Overview: The West Garrison, or Fort Reynolds, is a good spot for a picnic with a great view and historic buildings. $3 State Park day use fee.

Facilities: Restrooms, picnic tables.

Links: Angel Island State Park
Links: Bay Area Water Trail - Angel Island

title: Angel Island, Kayak Camp
details:
Overview: Kayak camp is the best site for camping. It is reached over a steep trail up the hill from the beach, which BASK installed years ago and is still functional. Stash boats above the high tide line in the bushes. Kayak camp can accomodate up to 20 people. Reserve it at 800-444-7275 or at ReserveAmerica.com . $3 State Park day use fee.

Parking: Ya can't drive there.

Facilities: Restrooms a short distance away, water, picnic tables.

Contact Info: CA State Parks camping reservations: 800-444-7275

Links: Bay Area Water Trail - Angel Island

details:

Facilities: Restrooms, picnic tables, snack bar.

Links: Bay Area Water Trail - Angel Island

details:
Overview: China Cove is the site of the historic immigration station on Angel Island. $3 day use fee.

Facilities: Restrooms.

Links: Bay Area Water Trail - Angel Island

title: Sam's Anchor Cafe, Tiburon
details:
Overview: Sam's Anchor Cafe has a guest dock which is quite high, full of splinters, and deteriorating. Visiting kayaks can be tied off behind the dock or pulled up onto the dock and stashed behind the gangway. Come from Sausalito, Horseshoe Cove or Ferry Point. It is a favorite spot for evening paddles from Sausalito. If you need a place to stay, the very chi-chi Waters Edge Hotel is right next door. This is a busy boating spot with the Corinthian Yacht Club on one side and the Angel Island Ferry on the other. Sam's has a new owner so maybe the docks will get upgraded.

Parking: There is a public pay parking lot at the end of the street. Or, if you are lucky there might be a free 2 hour spot on the street. Better to come by kayak.

Facilities: Bathrooms in both the restaurant and on the public dock next to the restaurant. Hours: M-Th, 11Am-11PM; Fri, 11AM-12AM, S/S, 9:30AM-11 or 12.

title: Glen Cove Marina
details:
Overview: This private marina doesn't offer a lot in the way of launch sites for hand held boats. Ask permission to launch from the guest dock. This is a nice stopping place for lunch (BYO). Although there is no formal campground they have also been known to allow kayakers to camp on their lawn!! Make friends and ask about it. Come here from Vallejo or Benicia.

Parking: There are about 20 spaces beside and behind the harbormaster's building. Free.

Facilities: Restrooms are in the marina office building and are open when harbormaster's office is open (9AM-5PM maybe). Boat storage is available. Inquire at the marina office.

Address: 2000 Glen Cove Marina Rd.

title: San Francisco, Pier 1.5
details:
Overview: Pier 1 1/2 is a city dock (high freeboard) which permits use of human powered vessels 24 hours, 7 days per week. Good place to visit the Ferry Building. For security reasons it is advisable to leave someone behind to watch the boats. The long range plan includes having a low float dock for kayakers at the rear of the large float. Note: during winter storms it has gotten rough enough here to rip out the large dock!

Parking: None

Facilities: Bathroom in the building. Nice restaurant with a deck. Right next door to the Ferry Building (bring money).

Address: Pier 1 1/2 on the Embarcadero. Owned by the Port of San Francisco.


Pier 1.5 in SF

title: San Francisco, Crane Cove Park
details:
Overview: Protected pocket beach. Opened 9-2020. Easy paddle from Islais Creek or Pier 52. Good spot for a picnic. Water quality may be questionable after heavy rain with run off. Pier 70 is an active Port facility pier so be careful of boat traffic and stay north and west of the buoys to reach the beach. There is a path from the street for boat dropoff at 18th St. and Illinois. The park is very popular with locals and is quite crowded on weekends.

Parking: There is a small parking lot at 19th St. and Illinois. Otherwise, forget it.

Facilities: Will include a boat house, water, bathrooms etc. Currently there are porta potties and a wash station. There is a nice lawn for picnics. Other facilities may be completed in 2021.

Address: 18th St. and Illinois. Beside Pier 70

Contact Info: Port of San Francisco

title: Mission Creek Kayak Launch Dock
details:
Overview: Launch from the low float dock. UCSF has a boat house here. Unload on the street and then good luck finding a place to put the car. From here tour the waterfront or stop here for a rest stop after putting in somewhere else more convenient. The dock is open from 6AM-10PM. Note: There is a sewer overflow and storm drain outfall right next to the dock. After heavy storms the water quality might not be so good. Don't fall in.

Parking: Metered parking is limited and on the street.

Facilities: There are bathrooms and drinking fountain at the west end of the park as well as a grassy area for a picnic and a sand volleyball court. The bathrooms are open 8AM-7PM.

Address: Mission Creek Park, 451 Berry St. Under the freeway

details:

Parking: Parking is free and limited to about 30 cars.

Facilities: Public bathroom. City Kayak operates out of the building and provides kayak storage as well as guided trips.

title: Pillar Point Reef
details: Overview: Great surfing spot! It tends to have smaller surf on the reef and larger breaks outside the reef near Sail and Mushroom Rocks.

title: Yellow Bluff
details:
Overview: On strong ebbs, big standing waves form downstream of the rocky point. There is a large eddy along the shore. It's like a merry-go-round for kayakers. If you didn't come to play, hug the shore.

Parking: If you just came to play, park at Horseshoe Cove.

Facilities: Presidio Yacht Club (PYC) serves beer for afterward.


Playtime at Yellow Bluff

title: Lake Tahoe, Fannette Island, Emerald Bay
details:
Overview: The only landing spot is in the shallows that face Vikingsholm Castle. Requires moving through bowling ball sized rocks and dismounting boat in ankle to knee deep water. Pull boat up onto shore afterwards because wakes by power boats can cause damage if left in the water.

It is a 3.5 mile paddle, each way, from Baldwin Beach to the south. Rental SOT kayaks are available (season permitting) at the shore South of Vikingsholm Castle (requires hiking down and back up).

Facilities: None.

title: The Women's Building (monthly BASK General Meetings)
details:
Overview: The monthly BASK General Meeting occurs on the last Wednesday of the month, 6:30 to 9:30 PM, at the Women's Building, 3543 18th St., San Francisco. We do not meet in November or December.

For more information on next meeting, check the Main Page of BASK website.

Public Transit: Take BART to the 16th Street Station--it's a short three block walk and takes about 5 minutes.

Parking: By special arrangement during the school year, we can park in the Mission High School lot on the west side of Dolores Street between 17th and 18th Streets (see marker on map). The parking driveway takes you up a ramp to an elevated parking slab behind a chain link fence. It is a two block walk to the Women's Building. We suggest you put something that says BASK on your dashboard. The lot will be locked at 10 PM so make sure you are out well before then. This lot is open only on nights when school is in session - closed on school holidays and during summer break. Check the BASK home page before arriving.

Address: The Women's Building, 3543 18th St., Mission District, San Francisco. We meet in the ground floor auditorium, just to the right of the main entrance.

Links: The Women's Building
Links: BASK

title: Glen Cove Waterfront Park in Vallejo
details:
Overview: There is a sand and small gravel beach that, at low tide, exposes to mud. The site is in a bight right on the Carquinez Strait so it blows upstream on summer afternoons. The far east end of the beach is flat sandstone. This might be a better destination than launch because of the limited parking and distance from parking to the beach and the stairs. Interestingly, this park is on the Bay Trail, the Ridge Trail and the Delta Trail.

Parking: Parking is on the dead end at the gate entering the park. It is about 200 yds to the old concrete steps leading down to the beach. Parking is free. No overnight parking allowed.

Facilities: None

Address: From highway 780 heading to Benicia take the Glen Cove off ramp. Turn left on Regatta and right on Whitesides and go to the end.

Contact Info: Greater Vallejo Recreation district, 707-648-4600

Links: http://www.gvrd.org

title: Santa Cruz harbor kayak launch, F
details:
Overview: There are two kayak launches on the west side of Santa Cruz Harbor. This is for the northern one and it has a small platform which will accommodate one boat at a time. Parking is nearby. From here explore the harbor or go out to explore the coast.

Parking: The parking lot is about 30-40 yds from the launch. There is no loading area. The fee is $12.50 for an auto with up to 2 kayaks and $6 for each additional kayak. There is an iron ranger that takes cash or credit cards. there are no time restrictions but overnight parking is not allowed

Facilities: There are bathrooms about 550 ft from the dock and about 100 ft from the parking lot. they are ADA and clean and well maintained but do not appear to be open around the clock.

Contact Info: Santa Cruz harbor,

details:

The parking driveway takes you up a ramp to an elevated parking slab behind a chain link fence. It is a two block walk to the Women's Building. We suggest you put something that says BASK on your dashboard. The lot will be locked at 10 PM so make sure you are out well before then.

title: Jim Hench Memorial Kayak Launch
details:
Overview: This wide concrete launch for kayaks and canoes is under the 1st St bridge. The ramp itself is often clogged with debris. From here you can go up river to Trancas Park (3 miles) or downriver to Cuttings Wharf (6 miles)

Parking: There is free parking for 1 car only on Soscol Ave. There is also parking for one car to unload. It is about 100' down a gently sloping concrete path to the ramp.

Facilities: None.

Address: Corner of 1st St and Soscol Ave. in downtown Napa

title: Santa Cruz Harbor Kayak Launch A
details:
Overview: The dock is a lego type dock designed for kayaks. Kayak storage is located at the top of the gangway. From here explore the harbor or head out to the coast.

Parking: Plenty of parking but quite a ways from the dock along a walkway often congested with tourists. Fees are $12.50 for an auto with up to 2 kayaks and $6 for each additional kayak (how would they know??). There is an iron ranger that takes cash or credit cards. No overnight parking allowed. Otherwise there are no time restrictions.

Facilities: Bathrooms are located about 550 ft from the dock (100 ft from parking lot). They are clean and well maintained. Aldo's restaurant is right next door. Kayak storage is also available here, call the harbor office for more details, 831-475-6161. There is a 1 1/2 year wait for a slot and the fee is $60/month.

Address: Off Edgewater Dr.

The owner does not want non-motorized boats using the concrete ramp so use the kayak launch. 101 Surf Sports is the outfitter located here and they have space to launch too. From here explore Bair Island, Redwood City or Westpoint Slough and Bedwell Park.

Parking: There is plenty of parking. Hours are 9AM-6PM. No overnight parking allowed.

title: San Francisco Marina - West End
details:
Overview: This unknown launch spot has a set of stone steps that lead down to a beach at lower tides. At higher tides the water comes right up to the steps. There is space to unload right next to the steps. This is the furthest back spot in the marina and it is very protected. You do still need to face the wind, currents, boat traffic etc once you exit the marina.

Parking: There is a large, free parking lot that is supposed to be for the Palace of Fine Arts very close to the launch. There is also free parking along Yacht Club Dr. There are no posted time restrictions but no overnight parking is allowed. Possibly crowded during events at the Palace but mostly it's pretty empty.

Facilities: Public Restrooms just to the west across the lawn (about 50 yds). It is open 8AM-8PM in summer and 8AM-5:30PM in winter. Bathrooms are ADA and there is a drinking fountain outside. The Dynamo Donut and Coffee is located right next to the water (open Fri-Sun, 8AM-4PM). No other amenities. There is grass for picnics or to just sit around.

title: Baker Beach
details:
Overview: This site has a sand beach that is usable at all tides. There are several paths from the parking lot to the beach. The surf dumps here and the size depends on the a variety of factors. The beach faces northwest, which is where the swell and the wind usually comes from. You will find tourists and happy dogs running on the beach. This is a somewhat advanced launch (ya need surf skills) as well as destination.

Parking: The lot is large and free. It closes one hour after sunset. No overnight parking is allowed. It is about 15-20 yds from the parking lot to the beach. There is space for unloading beside the paths that go to the beach.

Facilities: There are bathrooms at the rear of the parking lot that are clean and maintained. There is a picnic area with tables and with BBQs that is currently (4/2018) being renovated. There is running water available.

Address: Outside the Gate. Take Gibson Rd from Lincoln Blvd and go to "Day Use Area"

Contact Info: GGNRA, 415-561-4323 or 415-331-1540 (Visitor Center at the Headlands in Marin)

title: Benicia State Recreation Area
details:
Overview: This site provides access onto Carquinez Strait. The best launch used to be the remains of an asphalt ramp that went through the tule reeds to the water. The remains are still there but better are several informal paths to the water that don't require dragging over tule reeds. The distance you must carry your boat is about 20 yds and it is flat. There is room for rigging in the parking lot. You will find the shoreline muddy at low tide. This site is very protected from wind, however, once you leave the usual conditions of brisk summer winds (from the west) and currents due to the river apply.

Parking: There is a good sized parking lot with about 30 spaces. There is a $6 day use fee payable at and iron ranger. the lot is gated and open from 8AM to sunset.

Facilities: The location is on the Bay Trail and is well used by hikers, bikers and dog walkers. There are 2 porta potties. From here paddle east to Benicia or across the river to Port Costa or West to Vallejo.

Address: 1 State Park Rd. At the west end of town. Exit Military West from Hwy 780. It is an immediate right onto West K St and another immediate right into the parking lot.

Contact Info: City of Benicia Parks and Community Services, 707-746-4285 or try, 707-648-1911 for a ranger.

title: China Beach, San Francisco
details:
Overview: "Destination" because of the difficult access. There are over 100 stair steps to the beach. Young studly surfers do it all the time. There is also a long, employees only driveway that goes down the hill to a decrepit rusting building that houses the surf rescue guys' stuff. If you wind up swimming to the Farallones they will come and get you. The beach is sand and usable at all tides. The beach faces NW which is where the wind and swell usually come from.

Parking: If you drive, there is free parking for 38 cars. Overnight prohibition is not posted so who knows. This is a residential neighborhood. The park closes at sunset.

Facilities: There are three barely-maintained porta potties about 30 yds up the driveway from the beach. There is a picnic area with BBQ. No running water.

Address: End of Seacliff Dr. in San Francisco

Contact Info: GGNRA, 41-561-4323

title: Greyhound Rock County Park
details:
Overview: Sand beach. The path from the parking lot is about 300 yds down a steep path to the beach. It is paved most of the way with a small set of washed out steps at the end. There is spring seepage in a couple places that make it slippery. This is a well protected cove to launch once you make it to the beach. Launch on the south side of Greyhound Rock. The north side is rocky and covers a shallow reef.

Parking: 50+ spaces in a large parking lot. It is .12 miles to the beach. Parking is free from sunrise to sunset with no overnight parking allowed.

Facilities: There are pit toilets at the parking area which are sometimes dirty and unkept. There is a picnic area but no other amenities.

Address: 3564 Highway 1, 1.2 miles south of Waddell Creek State Beach

title: Waddell Creek State Beach
details:
Overview: Waddell Beach is part of Big Basin Redwood State Park and is supposed to be a world class windsurfing and kiteboarding spot. Hmm, northwest wind blows all the time they say.

Parking: Over 30 spaces in a large lot. There is no loading area but it is free. The lot is open 8AM to sunset with no overnight parking allowed. It's about a 200 ft carry to the beach.

Facilities: There are pit toilets in the parking lot (about 200 ft from the beach). Maintenance is so-so. There are no other amenities.

Address: 3640 Highway 1

title: Mono Lake, Navy Beach
details:
Overview: Gravel beach. You must stay one mile away from Paoha Island and Negrit Island from April 1 to August ! due to nesting season. Osprey nest on the tufa towers along the shoreline. You must stay 250 yds away from active nests (usually April 1-September). If you have not paddled on Mono Lake, GO! It is weird and spectacular. It is an alkaline lake so your kayak, gear and you will be coated with mineral deposits. Afternoon winds coming off the Sierra Nevada can ve significant during summer and fall. thunderstorms are also common in the late summer. Check with the Visitor Center for current conditions. DO visit the Visitor Center. They know all kinds of stuff about the flora, fauna, geology, hiking conditions, and are generally informative and cool.

Parking: There is parking for about 12 cars in the parking lot which is about 250 ft from the beach depending on the lake level. It is free and overnight parking is allowed.

Facilities: Zero. There is camping along Hwy 120 between Lee Vining and Tioga Pass. There is a kayak outfitter, Caldera Kayaks.

Address: Navy Beach is located at the end of Navy Beach Rd. You will have a map won't you?

title: Benicia/Martinez Bridge
details:
Overview: This is the best spot to launch to explore around what's left of the ghostly Mothball Fleet which is anchored only a mile away. Plan to launch near the end of the flood and return on the ebb. The Navy warns that for your own safety you must stay at least 100 feet away from the ships. Try to go when they are off duty. The launch is a micro beach that is immediately adjacent to the bridge tower. To get there you must carry your boat across the road (speeding trucks), the railroad tracks (slow moving but very long trains) and down rip rap boulders (possible broken legs). It's not as bad as it sounds. Currents at both flood and ebb tides are significant.

Parking: Parking is free in a small lot that fisherpeople use on the opposite side of the road from the water. It is supposed to be limited to 4 hours and no overnight parking is allowed.

Facilities: There is a porta potty in the parking lot. Otherwise, nada.

Address: Under the bridge on Bayshore Rd. near the corner of Oak Rd.

details:

You must stay one mile away from the island during bird nesting season (April 1- August 1). In hiking around the island you may discover the remains of an old spa resort. Camping is allowed here. details:
Overview: The River Heritage Center has a funky and wobbly set of docks behind the barn with five stair steps that go down to them. The site is operated by the Friends of the Petaluma River. The Heritage Center access is supposed to be open dawn to dusk and the road in is gated but it doesn't appear that the gate has been closed anytime recently. They hold river focused events periodically and give boat rides to the public on Sundays, 10AM-1PM. This is a better Destination than Launch. Come on Sunday and see the exhibits in the barn.

Parking: Parking is free but limited to about 12 cars. It is a LONG walk to the barn and the dock.

Facilities: There are 2 porta potties that are not well maintained.

title: Sandy Beach Park, Rio Vista
details:
Overview: This fully developed park has two launch ramps and a white sand beach. There is space for loading and unloading. The beach is down a gentle slope from the parking area and day use picnic area. The ramp is open 24 hour/day. Be aware that it is windy on summer afternoons (wind blows upriver) and there is current.

Parking: Lots of it and close to the ramp. $6/day use and parking. Overnight parking is available, check with the harbormaster.

Facilities: Camping, restrooms near the ramp, picnic area and BBQs. In the camping area three cars are allowed per site with a max of 10 people. There is a campground host. Overflow parking is no problem. This park also has a secure storage facility for boats. It costs $45/mo for trailered boats. The picnic area (day use) is open 8AM-6PM daily.

title: Rio Vista Municipal Boat Launch
details:
Overview: The ramp is closed during its renovation and is scheduled to reopen early in 2021. There is a double ramp with a $10 launch fee that is paid at an iron ranger. It takes cash or credit cards. By parking on the street or in the Park & Ride lot one could probably avoid the launch fee. Keep in mind that there are brisk up-river winds in summer. From here you can paddle to Brannan Island State Park or take a short jaunt to Sandy Beach Park

Parking: Lots of parking close to the launch ramp. Six spaces for non-trailered vehicles but there is plenty of additional parking in the adjacent Park & Ride lot.

Facilities: There are bathrooms (maintenance is so-so), drinking fountain, and benches along the river. This site is only about a block from the main street of town and eating opportunities.

Address: Foot of Montezuma St or Front Street behind City Hall

Links: http://www.riovistacity.com/boat-launchpicnic-area

title: Lake Solano County Park and Campground
details:
Overview: Lake Solano is part of Putah Creek. This lake is for non-motorized boats only. It has a concrete launch ramp with a mud beach beside it. There is a rigging area near the ramp (which has a high float dock). This is lake paddling. One side arm has a fabulous fig tree where you can pick ripe figs from your boat. There is no fee to launch, just for parking. It is possible to rent boats and you can borrow a waterproof Canoe Guide that points out interesting sights.

Parking: There are two lots, one is upper and one is lower. The parking fee is $6/day. No overnight parking is allowed at the lake.

Facilities: There are bathrooms, somewhat maintained, drinking fountain, picnic area and BBQ. There is also a hose for washing boats. Campground is right across the street and charges $25/day ($13/day for seniors).

Address: 8685 Pleasant Valley Rd, Winters

Contact Info: Lake Solano County Park, 530-795-2990

Links: http://www.co.solano.ca.us/depts/rm/countypark/lakesolano.asp

title: Brannan Island State Recreation Area
details:
Overview: This park has a ten-lane ramp (yes, 10 lanes!). This is a busy place in summer. There is a bike-in/kayak-in campsite near the launch ramps. Although it is windy in summer the launch faces south onto Threemile Slough and is somewhat protected from wind. It is 8.4 miles to Sugar Barge Marina on Bethel Island, 8.7 miles to Big Break, 8.9 miles to Sherman Island and 5 miles to the ramp in Rio Vista. There is a fee to enter. Day use is sunrise to sunset. The published fee schedules are quite extensive and complex depending on what you want. Call to find out. Although it is a state park it is managed by American Land and Leisure.

Parking: Plenty near the boat launch as well as at the campsites.

Facilities: Brannan Island Recreation Area is a fully developed park and campground. Besides camping it has day use areas with picnic facilities etc etc. Bathrooms with showers are located near the ramps as is the Campground Host. You can also rent a little cabin here.

Address: 17645 highway 160, Rio Vista

Contact Info: Park office, 916-777-6671

Links: http://www.americanll.com/brannan-island-sra
Links: http://www.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=487

title: Whitehouse Pool Park
details:
Overview: Launch from the mud bank. Best at high tide but OK at low tide too. An informal path leads to the water. From here paddle north to the Giacomini wetlands (bring binoculars) or up the creek as far as the tide will take you. This location is quite protected from the usual north wind.

Parking: Dirt lot for about 50 cars about 20-30 yds from the put-in. Parking is free and open 4AM-9PM with no overnight parking allowed.

Facilities: Porta potty and a picnic table.

Address: On Sir Francis Drake Blvd at the south end of Tomales Bay

Contact Info: Marin County Parks, 415-473-6387

title: Keys Creek Fishing Access
details:
Overview: The launch is over a mud bank/beach. The mud is firm. There are several informal paths through the trees to the creek. Once upon a time this creek went all the way to Tomales village. Not so now but you can go up Walker Creek. On high tide, see how far you can get. It's pretty. Or you can paddle to (or from) Nick's Cove in Tomales Bay.

Parking: There are 12-15 spots in a dirt lot. The lot floods when it rains. It is free. The posted time is sunrise to sunset with no overnight parking allowed.

Facilities: Porta potty which is clean and maintained. Picnic area.

Address: Off Shoreline Hwy (Hwy 1) between Tomales village and Tomales Bay

title: Rodeo Beach, Marin Headlands
details:
Overview: The sand beach is usable at all tides. There are 4 access point to the beach--2 sets of stairs, one dirt ramp and one bridge over the lagoon. At the far south end of the beach (not accessible by car) the surf is much lower and it is a nice place to stop for lunch. If you paddle from here into the Bay you will enjoy tunnels and arches (wear your helmet). This is a surfing beach. You need surf skills. It is a very popular place with board surfers. Know and practice surf etiquette.

Parking: There is a large parking lot that is often full on weekends. There are rigging areas by each of the access points. Parking is free with no time restrictions. Nothing is posted about overnight parking.

Facilities: Bathrooms with outdoor showers are located in the parking lot. There is a drinking fountain and a picnic area with BBQ.

Address: From Alexander Rd. take Bunker Rd to the Headlands. Veer left onto Mitchell Rd and go to the end.

title: Dipsea Cafe, Mill Valley
details:
Overview: High tide eating opportunity. Come here from Richardson Bay. Get out under the bridge. Stop to eat, and leave before the tide drops. If time and tide allow, head up the creek to explore. There is also the possibility of launching from the creek bank in the Dipsea parking lot. Did I say--High Tide Only! The Dipsea is open 7AM-3PM.

Parking: Park wherever you put in.

Facilities: Dipsea is one of Marin's legendary cafes. They have bathrooms and good basic food.

Address: 200 Shoreline Hwy, Mill Valley

title: Blackies Pasture, Tiburon
details:
Overview: High tide launch into Richardson Bay. The beach is sand at high tide and sucking mud at low tide. From here you can go to Sausalito to tour the houseboats or to upper Richardson Bay. The real attraction are the birds so bring binoculars. This section of Bay is closed from October to March to protect migrating birds from the likes of us.

Parking: Parking is free and the lot is large. The park is popular with dog walkers, hikers and bikers and, therefore, busy. There are no time restrictions posted.

Facilities: Bathrooms and drinking fountains are about 100 yds away.

Address: Tiburon Blvd between Reed Ranch Rd and Trestle Glen Blvd

Contact Info: City of Tiburon, 415-435-3373
Tiburon Peninsula Foundation, 415-499-6387

title: 3rd Street Bridge Beach, Napa
details:
Overview: There is a nice sand beach at all tides where you can stop for lunch or to rest. The building up behind is undergoing a major reconstruction so there is no access from the road or the bridge at present (2018).

Parking: None

Facilities: None

Address: 3rd Street bridge, northeast side, downtown Napa

title: Strawberry Cove Park, Strawberry
details:
Overview: The spot to launch on high tides is 20-30 yds beyond the workout area. Launch at a high ebbing tide at the mouth of Belloc Lagoon which is sensitive bird habitat. Bring binoculars but resist going in there. Besides it is wicked mud. Although not subject to closure, migrating birds abound from October to March so be respectful. The launch area is pebbles and firm mud which gets softer as the tide recedes. From here explore upper Richardson Bay or head south for a houseboat tour in Sausalito.

Parking: About 20 spots on the street.

Facilities: Drinking fountain, benches, picnic tables and a workout area but no bathrooms.

Address: 106 Seminary Dr across the street from the Strawberry Shores Apartments.

Contact Info: Strawberry Recreation Dept., 415-383-6494


Strawberry Cove Park, lagoon entrance, high tide, 3-3-18

title: Lexington Reservoir, Los Gatos
details:
Overview: This park has a launch ramp for non-motorized boats only. There is a low dock at higher water levels, a dirt ramp that is usable at all water levels and a gravel beach. Fees are: $6 parking, $5 launching, $4 quagga inspection. The park is open from 8AM to sunset.

Parking: There are over 30 spaces about 100 yds from the launch with a loading area. No overnight parking allowed.

Facilities: There is a porta potty about 100 yds from the launch with multiple units that are maintained. There is a picnic area. No camping.

Address: Alma Bridge Rd in Los Gatos. 0.3 miles south of the dam.

Contact Info: Ranger (c), 408-334-3990
Parks office, 408-356-2729

title: Brooks Island Regional Preserve
details:
Overview: Brooks Island belongs to East Bay Regional Parks and is a very sensitive bird preserve. You can go there only on naturalist guided tours. BASK has done this several times and the visits are worth every bit of the trouble. Especially if you can schedule it in spring when the flowers are blooming.

Parking: Launch from Vincent Park.

Facilities: No food or water so bring your own and be prepared to pack out trash. There is a bathroom by the caretakers residence.

Address: Island is just south of the Richmond Harbor.

Contact Info: To schedule a tour, 1-888-327-2757 option 2

Links: for scheduled tours

title: Tower Park Marina
details:
Overview: This is a friendly marina where you can launch to head down the river or land after launching at New Hope/Wimpy's. This is a river so plan on going with the flow. It is flat water and beautiful. One significant risk factor is water hyacinth which can block the entire waterway and may require portaging. Like most places in the delta they charge to launch. From here to Sugar Barge on Bethyl Island is 15 miles.

Parking: Available in the marina.

Facilities: Tower Marina has kayak rentals and a little store with food and drinks. They also have camping facilities if you need them.

Address: 14900 W. Hwy 12 (near Lodi).

Contact Info: 209-369-1041

Links: http://www.towerpark-marina.com

title: New Hope Marina/ Wimpys Marina
details:
Overview: After launching from the Cosumnes Preserve this is the place to take out. It is 5.5 miles one way and being a river you will run a shuttle. New Hope Marina and Wimpy's Marina are right next to each other and both have launch ramps. From here to Tower Park Marina is 11 miles. Wimpys is very kayak friendly. From here destinations include Delta Meadows, and the Mokelumne river both north and south forks. The area is affected by tides so plan accordingly.

Parking: Available for $5

Facilities: Wimpy's has a restaurant with great food. Camping is available if you have an RV. During 2020 they are undergoing some construction. There is a porta potty. Pre-COVID, when the restaurant was open, regular bathrooms were available.

Address: New Hope, 13945 W. Walnut Grove Rd
Located 3 miles west of Hwy 5 (Thornton offramp).

title: Sugar Barge Resort
details:
Overview: Sugar Barge has a ramp and a restaurant. They charge $10 to launch a kayak. They also rent kayaks. Tent camping is available for $25/night. This is a great place to launch (and come back to) in winter to look at birds--sandhill cranes and tundra swans hang out here. It is 9.5 miles from here to Brannan Island State Park. 15 miles from Tower Park at Terminous.

Parking: Available near the ramp.

Facilities: Restaurant opens at 11AM on weekends. It's a nice place to sit while waiting for the tule fog to lift in winter. During the pandemic they are open for take-out.

Address: 1440 Sugar Barge Rd on Bethel Island

Contact Info: 925-684-9075 or 800-799-4100

Links: http://www.sugarbarge.com

title: Treasure Island, Clipper Cove Beach
details:
Overview: Sandy beach. Currently (11-2020) the north end is closed for construction. Beach faces east and is protected from wind and rough water.

Facilities: There are stairs that lead up to bathrooms that may or may not be open during the pandemic.

title: Oyster Point Marina, Launch Ramp
details:
Overview: The ramp is mainly for motorized boat but can also be used by kayakers. 30-40 yds south is another concrete ramp through the rip rap that was designed for windsurfers but is usable by any hand carried boat. It does get windy here. Consider trips heading north as the SF airport is just to the south.

Parking: Free parking. Marina is open from 5:30AM-10:30PM. There is a loading area next to the ramp.

Facilities: The marina has bathrooms and offers kayak storage which is located by the harbormaster's office. There is a ferry landing inside the marina so be mindful of arriving and exiting ferries.

Address: 95 Harbormaster Rd. South San Francisco

Contact Info: Harbormaster, 415-952-0808 or 650-871-7344. Hours are 9-4PM M-F.
San Mateo Co. Harbor District, 650-726-4723

title: San Leandro Marina, informal ramp beside El Torito
details:
Overview: This very wide concrete ramp is usable at high tides only. At low tide there is a great deal of mud.

Parking: Free in the parking lot beside El Torito and immediately adjacent to the ramp.

Facilities: El Torito restaurant. You might be able to sneak into El Torito to use the bathroom but don't count on it.

title: Tiscornia Park, American River Parkway
details:
Overview: Tiscornia Park has a long sandy beach and is located at the confluence of the American and Sacramento Rivers. Land here after paddling the Parkway or launch here for trips down the Sacramento River. The take-out will be on river left just below the Hwy 5 bridge. This is also a good landing spot if you are going down the Sacramento River. There is a now-defunct launch ramp. There is a bridge inside the park that goes to Discovery Park.

Parking: There are three separate parking bays for about 40 spaces. The distance from parking to the water is 60-80 yds depending on where you park. The park is open 6AM-8PM. There is an entry fee.

Facilities: Bathrooms, picnic area, BBQ, drinking fountain.

Address: 195 Jibboom St. Sacramento

Contact Info: 916-808-6060 or 916-808-6068

title: Discovery Park, Sacramento River
details:
Overview: There is a large concrete launch ramp . This is a good place to either begin or end trips on the Sacramento River. It is also an easy round trip up river to the Virgin Sturgeon, a salty-sea-dog bar on the river. Tie your boat to the dock, go have a drink, and then casually float back to your car. The launch fee is $8 for a car with a kayak and $3 for each additional kayak. The launch ramp is in a small side slough just off the Sacramento River.

Parking: Parking is ample. The entry fee is $5 per car plus $3 per kayak. The park is open 6AM-8PM.

Facilities: Bathrooms, drinking fountains, picnic tables, BBQ. No camping.

Address: 1600 Garden Highway, Sacramento

Contact Info: Sacramento County Regional Parks

Links: http://www.regionalparks.saccounty.net/Parks/Pages/DiscoveryPark.aspx

title: Howe River Access, American River Parkway
details:
Overview: There is both a concrete launch ramp and a cobble/sand beach. Good take out if running the lower American River. It is 13 miles down from Sunrise and 5.7 miles down from Riverbend. The take-out is on river left above the Howe Ave. bridge. If you go downriver from here you can take out at Paradise Beach (looong carry) or Tiscornia Park (7.8 miles).

Parking: There is ample parking. Entry fee is $5 per car plus $3 per kayak. If it is hot try to park under the Howe Ave. bridge in the shade.

Facilities: Bathrooms, no water, no camping

Address: 7971 La Riviera Dr. Sacramento

title: Watt Avenue Access, American River Parkway
details:
Overview: There is a concrete boat launch as well as several cobble/sand beaches. Good take-out if running the lower Sacramento. As you approach the Watt Ave. bridge from upriver, plan to take out below the bridge. Stay left of center until you are through the "rapids", then hook to the left to get to the beach. Go a little further to take out at the boat ramp and avoid a carry. It is 10.75 miles downriver from Upper sunrise and 4.3 miles downriver from Riverbend.

Parking: There is ample parking. Try to get under the bridge if it is hot. Entry fee is $5/car plus $3/kayak.

Facilities: Bathrooms. No water, no camping.

title: Upper Sunrise Put-in, American River Parkway
details:
Overview: There is a concrete launch ramp. Great place to launch for lower American River paddle. Travel downriver on Class l water, with one Class ll (San Juan) rapid. The first 2 miles down river is ripply water, a few bridges, and on hot summer days, crowded with tubers and floaters. Arrive early to avoid the carnival. From here it is 7 miles downriver to Riverbend Park.

Parking: Ample parking but it's good to arrive early on hot summer days. Drive to launch and drop boats in staging area. Entry fee is $5/car plus $3/kayak.

Facilities: Bathrooms. No picnic area, no drinking water, no camping.

Contact Info: 916-875-6971

title: Lower Sunrise Put-In, American River Parkway
details:
Overview: Lower Sunrise put-in is more popular than Upper Sunrise so plan on getting there early. 6.5 miles to Riverbend Park. The first two miles downriver are Class l with a single Class ll (San Juan) rapid.

Parking: Ample parking. Entry fee is $5/car plus $3/kayak. Open sunrise to sunset.

Facilities: Bathrooms but no drinking water, no picnic area and no camping.

Contact Info: 916-875-6961
