title: Riverbend Park, American River Parkway, Sacramento
details:
Overview: This is the first take-out location if paddling the American River from Upper or Lower Sunrise put-ins. Great picnic spot for mid-paddle break if continuing downriver. Note: there are a few intermediate take-out locations along the river, but not advised because of low-patrol and car break-ins. If continuing downriver from here, go down the main channel (river left) after the footbridge, as the right channel has many strainers. There's a cute little rapid (Arden Rapid) just below the bridge, non-technical, just relax and avoid the one big rock in the middle. From here it is 4.3 miles to the Watt Ave. take-out.

Parking: Ample parking. If taking out, there is a long carry uphill to the parking and picnic area. This can be avoided by paddling the 4.3 miles downriver to Watt Ave. Entry fee is $5/car plus $3/kayak.

Facilities: Bathrooms and drinking fountain. Large picnic area. No camping.

Address: 2300 Rod Beaudry Dr, Sacramento

Contact Info: 916-875-7275

title: Nimbus Flat, Lake Natoma
details:
Overview: Concrete boat ramp or cobble/sand beach. Lake Natoma offers 14 miles (round trip) of powerboat-free paddling. Sloughs on the north side of the lake provide quiet access to wildlife. Paddling east you'll reach three bridges: Folsom Crossing, the iconic Rainbow Bridge, and the Iron Footbridge. Beyond that you'll be in a steep canyon with current, depending on flow out of Folsom dam. Note: at the top of the canyon there is a sign indicating the Folsom Prison property--Do Not Cross the Line.

Parking: There is ample parking with a $10 fee. A CA state "Poppy" pass is good here. Park is open sunrise to sunset.

Facilities: Bathrooms, picnic area, no camping. Site is adjacent to the Sac State Aquatic Center where rental boats are available.

Address: 7806 Folsom Auburn Road.

Contact Info: 916-988-0205

title: Willow Creek, Lake Natoma
details:
Overview: Concrete boat ramp or cobble/sand beach. Lake Natoma provides 14 mile of lake paddling. Go east to the three bridges--Folsom Crossing, Rainbow Bridge and the Iron Footbridge. East of there the canyon narrows and there may be current depending on water release from Folsom dam. When you get to the Folsom Prison sign, STOP and turn around.

Parking: Ample parking. $10 fee applies unless you have a CA state "Poppy" pass. Park is open sunrise to sunset (7AM-7PM).

Facilities: Willow Creek access is serviced by CCK which has weekend boat rentals. Pit toilets, picnic area, no camping.

title: Englebright Lake, Joe Miller Launch Ramp
details:
Overview: The Joe Miller concrete ramp is by the Skipper's Cove Marina. Englebright Lake is the dammed portion of the Yuba River. It has steep canyons with occasional waterfalls in winter and spring. The best time to enjoy this lake is late winter and early spring, before the power boats venture out. At the east end, Point Defiance, there is a fork. Go north to find more campsites before the river narrows to unnavigable. Land at Point Defiance and hike the one-mile trail to the Bridgeport Covered Bridge, the longest single-span covered bridge in America. There is another ramp by the Army Corps headquarters on Englebright Dam Rd.

Parking: There is ample parking at both boat launches. Parking and camp fees apply. Day use fee is $5 and camping fee is $20.

Facilities: There are 110 campsites. Bring your own water. Camping is dispersed around the lake. Campsites have pit toilets, picnic tables and campfire rings.

Address: Englebright Lake is located 21 miles east of Marysville off Hwy 20 on Mooney Flat Rd.

title: Lake Clementine, near Auburn
details:
Overview: Lake Clementine is the dammed portion of the North Fork of the American River (above Folsom Lake). The launch ramp is just above the Lake Clementine Dam. This area is called Lower Lake Clementine. The Lake is surrounded by steep canyon walls. Best enjoyed in autumn, winter and spring before the ski-boat crowd arrives. Power boats are restricted to a circumscribed path in a counter-clockwise direction so they are easily avoided. Come here for relaxed paddling and kayak camping. There is another put-in further up the canyon called Upper Clementine Beach which is open seasonally.

Parking: Parking is limited and gets used up quickly by boats/trailers in warmer weather. This benefits kayakers because boat traffic is limited by parking. Day use fee is $10 and $38/night for camping. CA park pass gets you in for free but does not cover camping. It is open 8AM-sunset year around.

Facilities: 13 boat-in campsites (first come, first served) that are interspersed around the lake. They have pit toilets, picnic tables and fire rings. Bring your own water.

Address: Lake Clementine Rd is off the Auburn-Foresthill Rd about 2 miles from Auburn.

title: Sailor Bar Park, American River Parkway, Fair Oaks
details:
Overview: This launch ramp is at the top of the American River Parkway and just a bit below the dam. From here head down river, after you've run a shuttle of course, to wherever you want to go downstream. This is a busy site in summer.

Parking: About 15 spaces near the launch ramp and a large parking area very nearby. Fees are $5/car and $3/kayak. There is a rigging area by the ramp. Road and parking are gravel (i.e. mud in winter). Hours are sunrise to sunset year around.

Address: 4253 Illinois Ave, Fair Oaks (park entrance). Ramp is at the end of Illinois Ave.

title: Pillar Point Harbor Launch Ramp
details:

Parking: Lots of parking. There is a $14 launch fee payable at an iron ranger that is mainly for parking in the adjacent lot. There is a 20 minute limit loading zone. The distance from the loading zone to the beach is about 20 yds.

Facilities: Bathroom is clean and well-maintained. Water at fish cleaning station.

title: Warm Water Cove
details:

From here paddle to Islais Creek or the SF waterfront. Or, go east to Alameda Island. Keep an eye open for ships. There is also a landable beach at the south end of the park.

title: San Francisco, Heron's Head Park
details:
Overview: Heron's Head Park was renovated in 2012. There is a nice hard packed pebble/sand/mud beach to the left of the trail about 300 yds from the parking lot. This is also called Lash Lighter Basin. Cargo ships come in here so be cautious. The park has a long trail out to the spit which goes along a restored meadow/grassland/marsh. There is a native plant nursery by the park entrance. From here tour the SF shoreline to the north, go to Candlestick Park to the south or just around the corner to India Basin.

Parking: Free parking for about 20 cars.

Facilities: Bathroom by the parking lot.

Address: Corner of Jennings and Cargo Way in Hunters Point. It is very close to India Basin Park.

Contact Info: Port of San Francisco, 415-274-0400

title: Blu Harbor Marina, Redwood City
details:
Overview: Blu Harbor Marina is at the site of the former Pete's Harbor. There is a low dock with a straight ramp from the parking area. The site is open during daylight hours. The access spot is between the dock and the rubble bank. The photo was taken at a 5-1/2' tide so it could be tight at low tide.

Parking: About a dozen spaces not reserved for tenants.

Facilities: Bathroom is not obvious. There is a hose bib for washing gear.

Address: 1 Blu Harbor Blvd. in Redwood city

Contact Info: Office: 650-395-9650 (8:30AM-5PM)

title: Cooley Landing Park
details:
Overview: High tide water access spots are to the south and also behind the education center. At low tide there is lots of mud. Park is fairly new and part of Ravenswood Open Space Preserve.

Parking: There are two parking areas. One just to the left as you enter the park and the other in front of the education center.

Facilities: Bathrooms and drinking fountain in the education center. Picnic area,

Address: East end of Bay Rd in East Palo Alto

Contact Info: City of East Palo Alto, Parks and Rec. 650-853-3100

title: Stinson Beach
details:
Overview: Stinson Beach is a 3 mile long beach. Water is shallow and the surf can be mild or wild. At low tide it spills. It is famous with tourists and locals alike. There is abundant parking. The carry from the parking lot to the water is less than 100 yds over flat ground. They warn of shark attacks at this site.

Parking: Abundant in several parking lots. entrance opens at 9AM every day.

Facilities: Clean, well maintained bathrooms with changing rooms and drinking fountains. Outdoor shower at the central bathroom. There are picnic areas with BBQ grills.

Address: Park entrance is at the north end of town, off Shoreline Highway and is labeled with a sign that says Stinson Beach Federal Park.

details:

title: Wimpy's
details:
Overview: Wimpy's is a restaurant that has a launch ramp with some parking available. The ramp is being renovated (2020) but is normally open 24 hours a day. There is a $5 launch fee.

Parking: Lots in front of the restaurant. About a dozen spaces by the ramp however this area is being converted to other uses.

Facilities: Food, drink and bathrooms in the restaurant. There is a porta potty available too.

details:

title: Garcia Bend City Park, Sacramento
details:
Overview: Garcia Bend Park is a local neighborhood park. To get to the concrete boat ramp, drive up and over the levee. There is a high dock on the right side. It is in a small pocket off the Sacramento River. There is a loading area for three cars at the top of the ramp. There is a fee to launch.

Parking: There is ample parking.

Facilities: Bathrooms. Picnic area, BBQ

Address: 7654 Pocket Rd., Sacramento

title: Millerton Point, Tomales Bay
details:
Overview: Millerton Point is a mid-to-high tide launch site that gives access to the southern part of Tomales Bay or makes a good start or end point for a one-way paddle to Nick's Cove. Located across the Bay from Inverness, you have a good view of the wreck of the Point Reyes outside the Inverness Market.

Parking: Free parking, which does not fill up until later in the day, even on hot summer days. There is a 300ft carry to the water, down a narrow path, on which wheels would not work.

Facilities: Pit toilet and nothing else.

Address: 15475 Hwy 1, north of Point Reyes Station.

Contact Info: Tomales Bay State Park

title: Sand Cove Beach Park, Sacramento
details:
Overview: There is a wide sand beach. The park has a gate so is probably locked at night. It is quite popular with fisherpeople.

Parking: There are 46 parking spaces. It is about 1000' to the shoreline. The path is wide enough for a cart and is mostly flat. The path ends at a short bluff above the beach with a well worn path down the slope.

Facilities: Two porta potties (one is ADA). No other amenities.

Address: 2005 Garden Highway, Sacramento

Contact Info: Sacramento City Department of Parks and Recreation, 916-808-5200

title: Tennessee Valley Beach, Mill Valley
details:
Overview: Tennessee Valley Beach is a lovely southwest facing beach. The beach landing is steep and the waves dump. Choose your set carefully and try to come in on the back of a breaking wave. This not a beginner's spot. It is quite popular with locals especially if the weather is good (i.e. not foggy). The beach is named for the ship Tennessee which wrecked here. Parts of the ship can sometimes be seen.

Parking: It is 1.8 miles up the valley to the parking lot along a good trail/fire road.

Facilities: There are no facilities at the beach. The nearest bathroom is up the trail aways.

Address: Between Muir Beach to the north and Rodeo beach to the south.

Contact Info: Golden Gate National Recreation Area

title: Parkside Aquatic Park, San Mateo
details:
Overview: Flat-water put-in on Seal Slough. There is a sandy beach and also a launch ramp. Popular on weekends. The "slough" is enclosed and you can paddle about one mile in each direction. Water is controled by pumps and quality is iffy.

Parking: Plenty of free parking.

Facilities: Bathrooms, grass for picnics.

Address: At the end of Seal St.

Contact Info: City of San Mateo, 415-377-3340
